text:
Key Concepts
Fluid Grids

Use percentage-based widths instead of fixed pixels

Flexible Images

max-width: 100%; height: auto;

Media Queries

Apply styles based on screen size:
@media (max-width: 600px) {
    body {
        background-color: lightgray;
    }
}

How CSS is Applied

Inline CSS (style attribute in an element).
Internal CSS (&lt;style&gt; tag in &lt;head&gt;).
External CSS (linked .css file).

/* Example External CSS */
h1 {
  color: blue;
  font-size: 24px;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
}

CSS Positioning - Example
Modify the position of elements with relative, absolute, and fixed values:
.box {
  position: relative;
  top: 20px;
  left: 10px;
}

Flexbox - Example Layout
Creating responsive layouts with Flexbox
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;  // Centers items horizontally
  align-items: center;      // Centers items vertically
}

.item {
  flex: 1;                 // Makes items grow equally
}

Grid Layout vs Flexbox

Grid: Use for two-dimensional layouts (rows and columns)
Flexbox: Use for one-dimensional layouts (row or column)

Defining rows and columns:
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
}

Grid Layout - Example
Using grid-template-rows, grid-template-columns, and grid-gap:
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-rows: 200px 1fr;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr;
  grid-gap: 20px;
}

Responsive Grid Layouts
Use media queries to adjust layouts dynamically:
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .container {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
}

Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) Principles


Operable - site must work without a mouse.

Example: Users navigate menus with Tab/Enter.

&lt;a href="contact.html" tabindex="0"&gt;Contact Us&lt;/a&gt;
button:focus {
  outline: 2px solid blue;
}



  &lt;a href="#main-content" class="skip-link"&gt;Skip to Main Content&lt;/a&gt;

Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) Principles


Understandable - content should be easy to read.

Example: Use clear labels, avoid jargon.

&lt;label for="email"&gt;Enter your email:&lt;/label&gt;
&lt;input type="email" id="email" placeholder="you@example.com"&gt;
Robust - Content should work across different browsers, devices, and assistive technologies.

Example: Use semantic HTML elements so screen readers and future technologies can interpret content correctly.


&lt;button type="submit"&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;

Media Queries: Adapting Layouts
Syntax
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  body {
    background-color: lightblue;
  }
}
Common Breakpoints

Small screens: max-width: 600px
Tablets: max-width: 768px
Desktops: min-width: 1024px

Flexible Grids: Fluid Layouts

Use percentages instead of fixed widths
Example:

.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));
  gap: 20px;
}
Using Flexbox for Responsiveness
.flex-container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 10px;
}
.flex-item {
  flex: 1 1 200px;
}
Demo: Flexible Grid Layout
Grid Example

Responsive Images
max-width for Scalability
img {
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
}
picture for Adaptive Images
&lt;picture&gt;
  &lt;source srcset="https://dummyimage.com/1024x600/000/fff" media="(min-width: 1024px)"&gt;
  &lt;source srcset="https://dummyimage.com/600x400/000/fff" media="(min-width: 600px)"&gt;
  &lt;img src="https://dummyimage.com/400x300/000/fff" alt="A responsive image"&gt;
&lt;/picture&gt;
Image Optimization Tips

Use modern formats like WebP for smaller file sizes
Implement lazy loading with loading="lazy"
Serve different image resolutions with srcset

Interactive Exercise
Modify this example to be fully responsive:
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  justify-content: space-around;
}
.card {
  width: 300px;
  margin: 10px;
}
Challenge: Make the .card flexible with media queries!

Advanced Media Queries
Combining Conditions
@media (min-width: 600px) and (max-width: 900px) {
  body {
    font-size: 18px;
  }
}
Orientation-Based Styling
@media (orientation: landscape) {
  body {
    background-color: lightgray;
  }
}
Demo: Responsive Background
(Try resizing the browser!)
Example Image

Mobile-Friendly Typography

Use relative units (em, rem, vw, vh)
Set line-height for better readability
Example:

body {
  font-size: 1rem;
  line-height: 1.6;
}

Skip Links

Allow users to skip navigation.

&lt;a href="#main-content" class="skip-link"&gt;Skip to content&lt;/a&gt;

Reduce Motion for Sensitive Users

Use @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) in CSS.

@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  * { animation: none !important; }
}

Lazy Loading Impact

Use loading="lazy" carefully; ensure content is still accessible.

&lt;img src="image.jpg" alt="Example" loading="lazy"&gt;

Accessible Loading Indicators

Use ARIA live regions to announce loading states.

&lt;div aria-live="assertive"&gt;Loading, please wait...&lt;/div&gt;

Touch Targets

Ensure buttons are at least 44x44px.

button { min-width: 44px; min-height: 44px; }

Zoom and Scaling

Avoid disabling zoom in meta tags.

&lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1"&gt;

Right-to-Left (RTL) Support

Use dir="rtl" for proper text direction.

&lt;body dir="rtl"&gt;

Language Attributes

Helps screen readers pronounce text correctly.

&lt;p lang="fr"&gt;Bonjour!&lt;/p&gt;

Prefers-Reduced-Motion for Sensitive Users

Use @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) in CSS.

@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  * { animation: none !important; }
}

Performance & Accessibility
Lazy Loading Impact

Use loading="lazy" carefully; ensure content is still accessible.

&lt;img src="image.jpg" alt="Example" loading="lazy"&gt;
